<br>
Hmmm, I would personally use ODS, unless I have the chance at something that's of Planar/Dragon drop quality. Even then, I would hesitate in doing so.<br>
<br>
I talked about this before on Graffle and also posted a message here referring to that post. Due to the volume of that board, my  posts had been delete, I think.<br>
<br>
I will repeat my points in that post. Hopefully a shorter version of it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The percentage on all focus effect is a random percentage from 1% to whatever the max percentage of that effect. The only exception to that is extend enhancement. <br>
<br>
Extend Enhancement had been changed by VI since people were complaining that it makes the job of the buffers more difficult. With the random percentages come the random durations of one buff to the next...So, Extend Enhancement has a fix duration.<br>
<br>
When you calculate the amount of mana you save by having the focus effect, I guess you will have to take the average percentage, which would be 5% out of 10% in the case of mana preservation.<br>
<br>
However, you then should multiply that by 2, simply because of the fact that the time that is required for you to get back the mana to cast a particular spell would be 5% less on the average.<br>
<br>
Now, let's do some comparisons, shall we? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Let's take ODS and take away the Focus Effect and then add 120 mana to it. Would you think that it's a very nice item now? I would say yes. Remember though, 120 mana is a fix number. <br>
<br>
Now, let's look at Mana Preservation. You get 10% of mana reduction, resulting directly from 5% less mana in casting a spell, and an additional 5% indirectly by the fact that you only have to med up to 95% mana cost of the spell in order to cast it again.<br>
<br>
Let's say that you have a total of 2400 mana. With the addition of 120 mana, the total comes to 2520 mana. Now, let's see about the effect of Mana Preservation.<br>
<br>
Starting with 2400 mana, casting every spell cost you an average of 5% less mana. Effectively, you can cast as many spells as someboy who has 2520 mana.<br>
<br>
But that's not all. Once you are out of mana, with the Focus Effect, you only have to med up to 95% of the mana requirement having the focus effect, comparing to 100% when you don't have the effect. <br>
<br>
So, medding up to full, reaching 2400 mana will take you 5% less time than medding all the way up to FM than medding up to 2520 mana. Once reaching FM in both cases, the number of spells casted would end up with the same number of spells that can be casted.<br>
<br>
Adding them numbers up, using up all your mana and then medding back up to FM resulting you having 120 mana more when you have the focus effect than when you don't have it.<br>
<br>
Rember when I said that the percentages of focus effects scale up vs a fixed number that you would get from an item?<br>
<br>
Look at the example above. The second time you do what was mentioned above, you will end up with an additional 240 more mana, and that will keep adding up indefinately. 120 mana + 240 mana + 240 mana...etc...<br>
<br>
Even if you add 240 mana to the ODS instead of 120 as I did above, Mana Preservation would still win hand down. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I will be the first one to admit that I am not good with numbers. So, please go over my calculations and point out anything that's wrong. I would be much appreciated.<br>
<br>
I know, I know, it's a long post, but I can't help it. LOL<br>
<br>
However, I hope it helps clearing things up a bit. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
